    <!-- MASTHEAD -->
    <header class="masthead">
      <div class="masthead-eyebrow">
        Federal Records · Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms &amp; Explosives
      </div>
      <h1>New Era<br /><span class="of">of</span> Reform</h1>
      <p class="masthead-sub">
        The agency that wrote the regulations is the same agency now striking
        them off the books. Thirty-four actions. Five categories. The biggest
        ATF rollback in a generation.
      </p>
      <div class="masthead-meta">
        <span><b>Filed</b> April 7, 2026</span>
        <span><b>Actions</b> 34</span>
        <span><b>Repealed</b> 7 major</span>
        <span><b>Tax cut</b> $200 → $0</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- LEAD -->
    <section class="lead-section">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="lead-grid">
          <div class="lead-text">
            <p>
              <span class="dropcap">F</span>or four years the ATF told the
              firearms industry exactly what it thought of due process. Inverted
              shall-issue inspections into shall-revoke inspections. Decided a
              brace was a stock. Decided 80% blanks were finished receivers.
              Decided every guy at a gun show was an unlicensed dealer. Then
              lost in court. And lost again. And again.
            </p>
            <p>
              On <strong>April 7, 2026</strong> the same agency published a package
              it is calling the <em>New Era of Reform</em>. Thirty-four
              regulatory actions divided into five buckets — Repeal, Modernize,
              Reduce Burden, Clarify, Align — and a new internal directive,
              <strong>ATF Order 5370.1H</strong>, that draws an explicit line
              between paperwork mistakes and willful violations.
            </p>
            <p>
              Some of this is real. Some of this is the agency formalizing
              losses it had already taken in court. Some of it is conspicuously
              missing. This is the case file.
            </p>
          </div>

          <aside class="stamp-box">
            <div class="stamp-rotate">
              <div class="stamp-big">Repealed</div>
              <div class="stamp-meta">
                Enhanced Regulatory<br />Enforcement Policy
              </div>
              <div class="stamp-date">07 APR 2026</div>
            </div>
          </aside>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CATEGORY BREAKDOWN -->
    <section class="section section-rule">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <div class="section-num">§ 01 · Inventory</div>
            <h2>Thirty-four actions, five buckets</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="right">
            ATF taxonomy<br />self-classified
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="section-intro">
          The reform package is the agency's own count, in the agency's own
          words. Repeal is the loudest column. Modernize is the most boring,
          and, for most FFLs, the most consequential.
        </p>

        <div class="cat-grid">
          <div class="cat-cell">
            <div class="cat-cell-num">7</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-label">Repeal</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-bar"><i style="width:100%"></i></div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-cell">
            <div class="cat-cell-num">9</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-label">Modernize</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-bar"><i style="width:100%"></i></div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-cell">
            <div class="cat-cell-num">8</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-label">Reduce Burden</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-bar"><i style="width:100%"></i></div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-cell">
            <div class="cat-cell-num">6</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-label">Clarify</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-bar"><i style="width:100%"></i></div>
          </div>
          <div class="cat-cell">
            <div class="cat-cell-num">4</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-label">Align</div>
            <div class="cat-cell-bar"><i style="width:100%"></i></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- THE BIG REPEALS -->
    <section class="section section-rule">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <div class="section-num">§ 02 · The Repeals</div>
            <h2>What just got struck off the books</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="right">
            Five case files<br />in priority order
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- CASE 1: Zero Tolerance -->
        <article class="casefile" data-reveal>
          <div class="casefile-head">
            <div>
              <div class="casefile-id">Case file 01 · ERP-2021</div>
              <h3 class="casefile-title">Zero Tolerance Policy</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="casefile-status">
              <span class="stamp">Repealed</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="casefile-grid">
            <dl class="casefile-meta">
              <dt>Issued</dt>
              <dd>June 2021</dd>
              <dt>Formal name</dt>
              <dd>Enhanced Regulatory Enforcement Policy</dd>
              <dt>Replaced by</dt>
              <dd>ATF Order 5370.1H</dd>
              <dt>Effect on FFLs</dt>
              <dd>License revocations down sharply</dd>
            </dl>
            <div class="casefile-body">
              <p>
                Under the Biden directive, ATF Industry Operations Investigators
                were instructed to initiate <strong
                  >license revocation proceedings</strong
                > for any of five categories of violation regardless of whether the
                dealer had three errors or three hundred, and regardless of whether
                anyone got hurt. A bookkeeping error and a straw sale were treated
                identically.
              </p>
              <p>
                Revocations of FFLs jumped roughly five-fold. Most of the
                dealers pulled were small-town gun shops that had operated for
                decades without complaint and had no ability to absorb a
                revocation hearing.
              </p>
              <p class="pullquote">
                The revocation rate did not drop because dealers got better. It
                dropped because the policy got rescinded.
              </p>
              <div class="casefile-take">
                <span class="lbl">2A take</span>
                Killing this one undoes more real-world damage than any single court
                decision did. Dealers can breathe now. The policy was always lawless
                — it converted ATF inspectors into prosecutors with a quota.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- CASE 2: Pistol Brace Rule -->
        <article class="casefile" data-reveal>
          <div class="casefile-head">
            <div>
              <div class="casefile-id">Case file 02 · 2021R-08F</div>
              <h3 class="casefile-title">Pistol Brace Rule</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="casefile-status">
              <span class="stamp">Repealed</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="casefile-grid">
            <dl class="casefile-meta">
              <dt>Issued</dt>
              <dd>January 2023</dd>
              <dt>Effect</dt>
              <dd>Reclassified ~40 million pistols as SBRs</dd>
              <dt>Court status</dt>
              <dd>Vacated in Mock v. Garland (5th Cir.)</dd>
              <dt>APA violation</dt>
              <dd>Confirmed</dd>
            </dl>
            <div class="casefile-body">
              <p>
                ATF spent a decade telling people braces were not stocks. It
                published <strong>letters in writing</strong> approving them. Then
                in 2023 it reversed course and demanded that owners register, demill,
                surrender, or destroy. The Fifth Circuit vacated the rule and the
                agency lost again on the merits.
              </p>
              <p>
                The reform package now formally pulls the rule from the books.
                It was already enjoined or stayed across most of the country —
                this just makes it official.
              </p>
              <div class="casefile-take">
                <span class="lbl">2A take</span>
                Important but largely posthumous. The rule was already a dead letter.
                The win is precedent: an agency that reverses thirty years of guidance
                overnight will lose under the APA, and the agency now admits it.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- CASE 3: Engaged in Business Rule -->
        <article class="casefile" data-reveal>
          <div class="casefile-head">
            <div>
              <div class="casefile-id">Case file 03 · 2022R-17F</div>
              <h3 class="casefile-title">"Engaged in the Business" Rule</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="casefile-status">
              <span class="stamp">Repealed</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="casefile-grid">
            <dl class="casefile-meta">
              <dt>Issued</dt>
              <dd>April 2024</dd>
              <dt>Effect</dt>
              <dd>Treated single sales as dealing</dd>
              <dt>Litigation</dt>
              <dd>Texas v. ATF — DOJ dropped defense April 2026</dd>
              <dt>Statutory floor</dt>
              <dd>BSCA definition retained</dd>
            </dl>
            <div class="casefile-body">
              <p>
                The original "private sale at a gun show is a federal crime"
                rule. ATF stretched the statutory definition of "engaged in the
                business" so far that a single transaction could trigger an
                unlicensed-dealing prosecution. The Justice Department
                <strong>dismissed its own appeal</strong> in
                <em>Texas v. ATF</em> in April 2026 and the agency now formally rescinds
                the regulatory overreach.
              </p>
              <p>
                The underlying statutory text from the Bipartisan Safer
                Communities Act stays in place. So this is not a return to
                pre-2022 — it is a return to <strong
                  >only what Congress actually wrote</strong
                >.
              </p>
              <div class="casefile-take">
                <span class="lbl">2A take</span>
                The right outcome via the wrong vehicle. Congress wrote "with the
                principal objective of livelihood and profit" and the agency tried
                to delete those words. The text won. Read it. Then re-read BSCA —
                the statute itself is still bad.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- CASE 4: Bump stock language -->
        <article class="casefile" data-reveal>
          <div class="casefile-head">
            <div>
              <div class="casefile-id">Case file 04 · 27 CFR 478.11</div>
              <h3 class="casefile-title">Bump-Stock Language</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="casefile-status">
              <span class="stamp">Repealed</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="casefile-grid">
            <dl class="casefile-meta">
              <dt>Issued</dt>
              <dd>December 2018</dd>
              <dt>Aligns with</dt>
              <dd>Garland v. Cargill (2024)</dd>
              <dt>Mechanism</dt>
              <dd>
                Two sentences removed from three definitions of "machine gun"
              </dd>
              <dt>Surrendered devices</dt>
              <dd>~520,000 (no return mechanism announced)</dd>
            </dl>
            <div class="casefile-body">
              <p>
                The Supreme Court already settled this in <em>Cargill</em>: a
                bump stock does not convert a semi-auto into a machine gun, full
                stop. ATF is now scrubbing the regulatory definitions to match
                the statute the Court enforced.
              </p>
              <p>
                What is conspicuously absent: any program to return or
                compensate the half-million devices Americans surrendered or
                destroyed under the 2018 rule. The agency took those.
                <strong>It is not giving them back.</strong>
              </p>
              <div class="casefile-take">
                <span class="lbl">2A take</span>
                Symbolic cleanup. The substantive win was Cargill. The missing compensation
                program is the tell — agencies that claim error rarely make people
                whole.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- CASE 5: FFL Poster -->
        <article class="casefile" data-reveal>
          <div class="casefile-head">
            <div>
              <div class="casefile-id">Case file 05 · 27 CFR 478.103</div>
              <h3 class="casefile-title">Youth Handgun Safety Notice</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="casefile-status">
              <span class="stamp">Repealed</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="casefile-grid">
            <dl class="casefile-meta">
              <dt>Issued</dt>
              <dd>1994</dd>
              <dt>Affected</dt>
              <dd>~75,000 FFLs nationwide</dd>
              <dt>Reason given</dt>
              <dd>"Unnecessary regulatory burden"</dd>
              <dt>Practical effect</dt>
              <dd>One fewer poster on the wall</dd>
            </dl>
            <div class="casefile-body">
              <p>
                A small one. Every FFL was required to post the Youth Handgun
                Safety Notice in plain view of customers. Thirty years on the
                wall, no measurable safety effect, and the statutory disclosure
                is duplicative of the 4473.
              </p>
              <div class="casefile-take">
                <span class="lbl">2A take</span>
                Minor but useful. Every burden reduction is a precedent that the agency
                does not need to be told twice. Stack enough of them and the compliance
                bill on a small dealer actually shrinks.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- TAX BANNER -->
    <section class="wrap">
      <div class="tax-banner" data-reveal>
        <div class="tax-banner-grid">
          <div class="tax-amount">
            <span class="strike">$200</span>$0
          </div>
          <div class="tax-content">
            <h3>The NFA Tax is Dead</h3>
            <p>
              Effective <strong>January 1, 2026</strong>, the federal
              transfer-and-make tax on suppressors, short-barreled rifles,
              short-barreled shotguns, and "any other weapon" dropped from $200
              to zero. The reform package codifies the implementation and
              modernizes the eForm processing around it.
            </p>
            <p class="meta">
              <b>Caveat:</b> Registration · background check · Form 4 wait · all still
              in effect
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- WHAT WAS KEPT -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <div class="section-num">§ 03 · The Survivors</div>
            <h2>What did NOT get repealed</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="right">
            Read this column<br />before celebrating
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="section-intro">
          Reform packages are advertised by what they remove. The smarter read
          is what the agency chose to keep — every survivor is a deliberate
          choice, not an oversight.
        </p>

        <div class="kept-shell" data-reveal>
          <div class="kept-banner">
            <span class="pin">⚠</span>
            <h3>Still on the books</h3>
            <span class="label">— Hold your applause</span>
          </div>
          <div class="kept-list">
            <div class="kept-item">
              <span class="kept-item-mark">▸</span>
              <div>
                <h4>Frames &amp; Receivers Rule (2022R-05F)</h4>
                <p>
                  The "ghost gun" rule. ATF kept it. Even though SCOTUS upheld a
                  narrow reading in Garland v. VanDerStok, the underlying
                  redefinition of "frame or receiver" stays intact. The agency
                  had every chance to kill it here and passed.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="kept-item">
              <span class="kept-item-mark">▸</span>
              <div>
                <h4>Background-check infrastructure</h4>
                <p>
                  NICS, the 4473, the FFL system itself. None of it is touched.
                  This was never going to be on the table, but it is worth
                  saying out loud — federal background checks remain federal
                  background checks.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="kept-item">
              <span class="kept-item-mark">▸</span>
              <div>
                <h4>NFA registry for suppressors and SBRs</h4>
                <p>
                  Tax is gone, registration is not. Every can and every SBR
                  still rides through the same Form 4 process and lives forever
                  in the National Firearms Registration and Transfer Record.
                  Cheaper, not freer.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="kept-item">
              <span class="kept-item-mark">▸</span>
              <div>
                <h4>BSCA "engaged in business" statutory language</h4>
                <p>
                  Only the regulatory <em>expansion</em> got pulled. The Bipartisan
                  Safer Communities Act amendment that broadened the definition was
                  passed by Congress, signed by a president, and remains in force.
                  ATF cannot rewrite a statute it did not write.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ORDER 5370.1H -->
    <section class="section section-rule">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <div class="section-num">§ 04 · The Replacement</div>
            <h2>What replaces Zero Tolerance</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="right">
            Internal directive<br />operative now
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="order-card" data-reveal>
          <div class="order-seal">
            <div class="ring">
              <div class="ring-num">5370.1H</div>
              <div class="ring-lbl">
                ATF Order · Administrative Action Framework
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="order-content">
            <h3>The Adminstrative Action Order</h3>
            <p>
              <strong>ATF Order 5370.1H</strong> is the replacement framework. It
              instructs Industry Operations Investigators to draw an explicit distinction
              between
              <strong>willful violations</strong> and clerical errors, and to scale
              enforcement in proportion. Revocation is the last step on a ladder,
              not the first.
            </p>
            <p>
              The order also imposes new internal review checkpoints before any
              revocation proceeding can be initiated. In practical terms, a
              missing 4473 signature should no longer start a license-pull.
              Whether the field offices follow it is the next question.
            </p>
            <div class="frame">
              ▸ Tiered response<br />
              ▸ Willfulness inquiry required<br />
              ▸ Revocation only after demonstrated pattern<br />
              ▸ Internal review before adverse action
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- THE TAKE -->
    <section class="take">
      <div class="wrap wrap-narrow">
        <div class="take-head">
          <div class="pre">The Take</div>
          <h2>Real, partial,<br />and overdue</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="take-body">
          <p>
            This is the largest voluntary contraction of ATF authority in my
            lifetime, and it is also less than it advertises itself to be. Both
            of those things are true. Reform packages always read as victories
            on the page they are printed on. The trick is to read the column the
            agency did not print.
          </p>
          <p>
            Zero Tolerance was the worst of it and Zero Tolerance is
            <strong>gone</strong>. That alone is a structural win for small
            dealers. The pistol brace rule is dead in writing, not just in the
            courtroom. The bump-stock cleanup matches
            <em class="em-italic">Cargill</em>. The "engaged in the business"
            expansion is rescinded and the Justice Department dropped its own
            appeal — that is the rarest kind of admission a federal agency
            makes.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            The agency that wrote the regulations is the same agency now
            striking them off the books.
          </blockquote>
          <p>
            And the column the agency did not print: the frames-and-receivers
            rule survives. The NFA registry survives. The roughly 520,000 bump
            stocks Americans handed over are not coming back. The statutory
            expansion of "engaged in the business" that Congress passed in BSCA
            is intact and will outlive every administration that inherits it.
          </p>
          <p>
            The right way to read this package is as a
            <strong>policy retreat under court pressure</strong>, not a
            philosophical conversion. The cases that forced the agency to write
            this document — <em>Cargill</em>, <em>Mock</em>,
            <em>VanDerStok</em>, <em>Texas v. ATF</em> — all came from outside the
            building. ATF did not wake up. It was woken up. Repeatedly. By judges.
          </p>
          <p>Take the win. Catalog the survivors. Then keep litigating.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

